05560nam a22010815i 9780691221465DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20201993nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912214657 a10.1515/97806912214652doi  a(DE-B1597)572682  a(OCoLC)1226679730  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aLIT0040202bisacsh04a821/.910912201 aMcGann, Jerome J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBlack Riders :bThe Visible Language of Modernism /cJerome J. McGann. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©1993  a1 online resource (216 p.) :b35 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tINTRODUCTION: Modernism and the Renaissance of Printing, with Particular Reference to the Writing of Yeats, Stein, and Dickinson -- tPART ONE: A Revolution of the Word -- t1 "Thing to Mind": The Materialist Aesthetic of William Morris -- t2 Composition as Explanation (of Modern and Postmodern Poetries) -- tPART TWO: Dichtung und Wahrheit -- t3 The Truth of Poetry. An Argument -- t4 The Poetry of Truth. A Dialogue (on Dialogue) -- tAfterword -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a"English literature," Yeats once noted, "has all but completely shaped itself in the printing press." Finding this true particularly of modernist writing, Jerome McGann demonstrates the extraordinary degree to which modernist styles are related to graphic and typographic design, to printed letters--"black riders" on a blank page--that create language for the eye. He sketches the relation of modernist writing to key developments in book design, beginning with the nineteenth-century renaissance of printing, and demonstrates the continued interest of postmodern writers in the "visible language" of modernism. McGann then offers a philosophical investigation into the relation of knowledge and truth to this kind of imaginative writing. Exploring the work of writers like William Morris, Emily Dickinson, W. B. Yeats, Ezra Pound, and Gertrude Stein, as well as Laura Riding and Bob Brown, he shows how each exploits the visibilities of language, often by aligning their work with older traditions of so-called Adamic language. McGann argues that in modernist writing, philosophical nominalism emerges as a key aesthetic point of departure. Such writing thus develops a pragmatic and performative "answer to Plato" in the matter of poetry's relation to truth and philosophy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAmerican poetryy20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aArt and literaturezEnglish-speaking countries. 0aBook designzEnglish-speaking countries. 0aEnglish poetryy20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aModernism (Literature)zEnglish-speaking countries. 0aPrintingzEnglish-speaking countries. 0aVisual poetryxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh  aAesthetic movement.  aAlienation effect.  aBibliographical styles.  aBurning Deck (publisher).  aCalligraphy.  aChiswick Press.  aCritical theory.  aDialogical model.  aDidacticism.  aEpic theatre.  aFalsity.  aFound texts.  aGolden type.  aHeuristics.  aIconic condition.  aImagination.  aJournal writing.  aKelmscott Press.  aLiterary history.  aObjectivism.  aOulipo group.  aPapermaking.  aPostmodern works.  aReferentiality.  aSemiotics.  aTemporalities.  aTranscendentalism.  aVorticism.  aWhite Rabbit Press.  aWord frequencies.  aYeats, Lily.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://d